Cook,<br><br>
If my time frame is correct, you were &quot;in country&quot; when LBJ made the announcement that he wasn't going to &quot;seek reelection&quot;. Here was our President and Commander In Chief, who had committed our troops to a war WITHOUT a formal declaration, had taken this measure and when it became too much for him to bear, he decided he had had enough. The Commander In Chief took a powder, yet the fighting continued. To me, this was the turning point of the war. This was the signal of defeat.<br><br>
This represented the psychological, propaganda victory for the communists that you are searching for. I can see the people of Hanoi jumping for joy when the Commander In chief of the US, the most powerful man on earth, abandoned his troops.<br><br>
The conservative, right wing always claimed that the actual number of war protestors was *inflated* by the media. You can't have it both ways. <br><br>
The protestors were more of an irritant to Johnson and Nixon than they were a true indicator of US public opinion to the communists. The communists knew by the stumbling and bumbling of our policymakers that eventually they would win.<br>
The hippies, like Jane Fonda, were useful to them. But the real weakness they perceived was in the lack of committment on the part of our politicians - whose GREATEST SIN was their inability to explain our involvement in Vietnam in a way that could be understood by the US citizenry.<br><br>

